## 8. Edge Cases & Failure Handling

### 8.1 Dot Not Visible in Frame

**Description:** Camera is positioned such that the laptop screen strip is not captured, or the strip is too dark (ambient light overrides).

**Detection:** `SyncDotNotFoundError` during seeding (Step E1). SAM2 confidence consistently below 0.5 for > 50% of frames.

**Recovery:** Return error with frame numbers. UI instructs user to re-position camera before re-recording.

**Simulation:** Crop out bottom 120px of test PNG sequence and run seeding — should raise error.

**Log emitted:** `SYNC_DOT_NOT_FOUND { camera_id, searched_frames: 30 }`

### 8.2 Dot Wrap Coincides with Ball Roll

**Description:** The dot wraps (resets to left edge) during the ball roll phase, causing a large residual spike in the linear fit in that region.

**Detection:** Large residual outlier at a frame where the dot wraps. The TheilSen fit is robust to this.

**Recovery:** Wrap events are naturally handled as outliers by TheilSen regression. No special action needed.

**Log emitted:** `SYNC_WRAP_DETECTED { camera_id, frame_idx }` for each detected wrap.

### 8.3 Camera Drops Frames Mid-Recording

**Description:** `MediaRecorder` silently drops frames (e.g., due to CPU overload). This produces a gap in the video container timestamps but ffmpeg `-vsync 0` still extracts the frames sequentially.

**Detection:** Residual spike in the linear fit at the drop location. The fit slope (true FPS) remains valid because it is computed from the majority of frames.

**Effect on sync:** A dropped frame means one frame index corresponds to a larger-than-expected time delta. The master timestamp array will have an incorrect entry at that index.

**Mitigation:** The physics engine uses true timestamps only for velocity fitting windows; a single dropped frame may cause one flagged low-confidence point (from ball tracking), which the user corrects manually.

**Quantification:** At 30fps, a single dropped frame introduces a 33ms error at that specific frame. If the dropped frame is not within the velocity fitting window, there is zero impact on physics results.

**Log emitted:** `POTENTIAL_FRAME_DROP { camera_id, frame_idx, residual_px }` when residual > 3σ.

### 8.4 iOS MediaRecorder Produces Incorrect Container Timestamps

**Description:** Known iOS Safari bug where `.mp4` container timestamps drift or reset mid-recording.

**Detection:** `ffmpeg` extracts fewer frames than expected, or frame PNG files have unexpected gaps.

**Recovery:** The sync algorithm does NOT rely on container timestamps at all — it uses only frame index (sequential integer) and the linear fit. Container timestamp bugs do not affect sync accuracy.

**Log emitted:** `CONTAINER_TIMESTAMP_WARNING { camera_id, expected_duration_s, actual_duration_s }` if they differ by > 5%.

### 8.5 Only One Camera Available (Single-Camera Mode)

**Description:** User is running a single-camera planar experiment.

**Detection:** `camera_ids` in `SyncRequest` contains only `["cam0"]`.

**Recovery:** Run sync analysis on cam0 only. `sync.json` has only `cameras.cam0`. `phase_offset_ms` for cam0 is 0.0 by definition. Physics engine proceeds in single-camera mode.

**No error emitted.** Single-camera mode is a first-class supported configuration.

### 8.6 Laptop Tab Backgrounded During Recording (Metronome Freeze)

**Description:** Browser throttles `requestAnimationFrame` when tab is not in focus. The dot freezes.

**Detection:** Long horizontal stretch of constant x-position in the camera recording. SAM2 will still track the stationary dot, but the linear fit will have near-zero slope during that window.

**Recovery:** The constant-position window is detected as a regime with slope ≈ 0, which is a large deviation from the global slope. TheilSen regression will discount this window. However, if the freeze duration exceeds 50% of the recording, fit quality degrades unacceptably.

**Prevention:** Keep the laptop browser tab in focus. UI shows a warning overlay if the tab loses focus during recording.

**Log emitted:** `METRONOME_FREEZE_DETECTED { duration_ms }` if > 500ms constant-x region detected.

### 8.7 Clock Drift Exceeds 1000 ppm

**Description:** Phone clock drifts more than 1ms per second relative to true time.

**Detection:** The linear fit slope encodes the exact true FPS. If `|true_fps - nominal_fps| / nominal_fps > 0.002` (2000 ppm), log a warning.

**Impact:** The master timestamp array automatically corrects for any measured drift, regardless of magnitude. Even 10000 ppm drift is fully corrected.

**Log emitted:** `HIGH_CLOCK_DRIFT_DETECTED { camera_id, ppm: ... }`

