## 9. Accuracy & Error Sources

### 9.1 Sources of Sync Error

| Source                         | Magnitude (estimate) | Mitigation                                                |
| ------------------------------ | -------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------- |
| SAM2 centroid error            | ±0.3–0.5 px          | Sub-pixel weighted centroid; SAM2 mask quality            |
| Linear fit residuals           | ±0.3–0.5 px RMS      | TheilSen regression; long fitting window (>90 frames)     |
| Camera lens rolling shutter    | ±0.1 ms per line     | Not corrected (CMOS phone cameras); treated as systematic |
| Laptop screen refresh jitter   | ±0.5 ms              | Not corrected; dominated by above                         |
| `performance.now()` resolution | ±0.1 ms (browsers)   | Sufficient; not a bottleneck                              |

### 9.2 Error Propagation to Phase Offset

```
σ(phase_offset_ms) = σ(t_zero_ms_cam0)² + σ(t_zero_ms_cam1)²  [root-sum-squares]

σ(t_zero_ms_cam{i}) = (residual_rms_px / slope_px_per_frame) / true_fps * 1000.0
                     ≈ (0.5 / 20.0) / 30.0 * 1000.0
                     = 0.025 frame / 30.0 fps * 1000.0
                     = 0.83 ms  [per camera]

σ(phase_offset_ms) = sqrt(0.83² + 0.83²) ≈ 1.17 ms  [worst case at 0.5px residual]

At 0.3px residual (typical):
σ(phase_offset_ms) = sqrt(0.5² + 0.5²) ≈ 0.70 ms

With 90 frames per sweep (3s at 30fps) and the fit uses the intercept,
the uncertainty is further reduced by the leverage of many frames:
σ(intercept) = residual_rms * sqrt(Σn²/N) / (N * slope)  [OLS intercept uncertainty]
This typically reduces to < 0.5ms in practice.
```

**Design target: sync accuracy < 0.5ms achievable with > 90 sync frames and < 0.3px residual RMS.**

### 9.3 Rolling Shutter

Phone cameras use CMOS rolling shutters. A 30fps 1080p phone typically has a row readout time of ~15–25ms, meaning the top and bottom of the frame are captured at different times within the ~33ms inter-frame period.

**Impact on dot tracking:** The dot is in the bottom strip of the frame. All frames of both cameras capture the dot at the same fixed Y-position (bottom strip). Rolling shutter delay at the bottom of the frame is consistent and constant across all frames, so it introduces a fixed bias (not a random error) into the sync dot intercept.

**Impact on physics:** The ball is tracked at varying Y-positions in the frame (since it moves). Rolling shutter introduces a position-dependent timing error of up to ~10ms for a ball at the top of the frame vs the dot at the bottom. This is a known systematic error; quantification is out of scope for this module but should be documented in the physics accuracy budget.

### 9.4 Validation of Sync Accuracy

The sync accuracy is empirically measurable from the `sync.json` itself:

1. `fit_residual_rms_px` — lower is better; target < 0.5px
2. `fit_r_squared` — target > 0.99
3. `sync_accuracy_ms` — the propagated 1σ uncertainty on the phase offset; target < 0.5ms

