| Cameras processed sequentially by SAM2             | Avoid VRAM contention                | Run on separate GPU processes if multi-GPU available                           |
| Phase offset computed from intercept extrapolation | Simple; works well for linear motion | Use cross-correlation of dot trajectories for redundancy check                 |
| Rolling shutter not corrected                      | Complex to measure; small effect     | Add per-camera rolling shutter parameter from device specs                     |
| Single sync dot                                    | Simple to seed and track             | Two dots at different speeds would over-determine the clock model              |
| TheilSen regression                                | Robust but slower than OLS           | RANSAC with OLS inner fit for speed (if analysis time is a bottleneck)         |
| No real-time sync check                            | Post-hoc only                        | Add a real-time "dot detected" confidence indicator in the UI during recording |

### 14.2 120fps Native App Path

If 120fps capture becomes necessary (unlocks < 8ms frame period vs 33ms at 30fps), the phone client can be replaced with a Swift AVCaptureSession app. The interface contract is unchanged: the app uploads a single video file to `POST /api/upload-video`. The Visual Metronome and sync analysis pipeline require no modifications.

### 14.3 Hardware Sync Option

A future hardware sync flash (LED triggered by the laptop) could replace the Visual Metronome. The LED would produce a single bright frame in both camera sequences simultaneously. This would yield ~1-frame (33ms) accuracy without the linear fitting step — substantially less accurate than the current approach. The Visual Metronome achieves better accuracy with no additional hardware.

